gui-speedtest (1.2.0-1) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Cloudflare: upload chunk sizes bumped from 500K-5M to 1M-25M so TCP
    has time to ramp up and saturate the link before each sample ends.
    The old range measured warmup slope rather than steady-state
    throughput and reported ~30% low on fast connections.
  * OVH: now probes both public mirrors (Gravelines FR + Beauharnois CA)
    on first use and picks the lower-latency one. EU users hit Gravelines,
    North American users hit Beauharnois. No Asian mirror exists, so
    AS/OC users still see OVH's geography-bound throughput.
  * M-Lab upload: authoritative byte count now comes from the server's
    AppInfo measurement frames (ndt7 TEXT messages sent during the test)
    when available. Client-side counter remains as fallback. The client
    counter measures bytes handed to the socket send buffer, which on
    fast links overshoots the real wire throughput by a few seconds of
    buffer.

 -- Mahmud Farooque <farooque7@gmail.com>  Sat, 18 Apr 2026 20:15:00 +0600

gui-speedtest (1.1.3-1) unstable; urgency=medium

  * GUI: Cancel now actually cancels AND doesn't freeze the window.
    v1.1.1's cancel called resp.close() from the GUI main thread, which
    blocks waiting for internal urllib locks held by the worker thread's
    in-progress read() — symptom was "Is Not Responding" dialog from the
    window manager.
  * Root-cause fix: cancel() now calls socket.shutdown(SHUT_RDWR) on the
    response's underlying socket instead of resp.close(). shutdown() is
    thread-safe and non-blocking; the worker's read() returns immediately
    with a ConnectionError.
  * Chunk/latency loops now check backend._cancelled at each iteration —
    prevents starting a new HTTP request after the current one was
    interrupted by cancel. M-Lab download/upload/latency loops reset the
    flag at the start of each phase so a cancelled run can be re-run.

