gui-speedtest (1.1.0-1) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Ookla backend: availability check now verifies the `speedtest` binary
    identifies as Ookla's official CLI (parsing `--version` output for
    "Ookla"). The Ubuntu `speedtest-cli` package (sivel/speedtest-cli)
    also installs as `speedtest` but accepts different arguments — running
    our Ookla argv against it previously produced empty JSON output and
    a confusing "Could not parse" error. Now the picker simply omits
    Ookla when the wrong binary is on PATH.
  * M-Lab backend: latency now measured as the WebSocket handshake round-trip
    (create_connection timing) instead of HTTPS HEAD against the wss://
    endpoint. M-Lab servers return 405 Method Not Allowed for HEAD, so every
    sample failed in v1.0.x. Latency now shows real numbers.
  * M-Lab backend: client IP / ISP / location now enriched via ipify +
    ipwho.is so the GUI reports your actual connection instead of
    "Unknown". Mirrors the Cloudflare fallback and OVH patterns.
  * GUI: Cancel button during a running test. Start → "Cancel" (destructive
    styling) while running → reverts to "Run Again" on completion. Calls
    backend.cancel() which terminates Ookla subprocesses immediately; for
    HTTP-based backends the current chunk finishes or times out before the
    worker thread exits (phase-boundary check on self.cancelled).
  * Packaging: AppStream metainfo.xml (data/io.github.mmhfarooque.GuiSpeedTest.metainfo.xml)
    installed to /usr/share/metainfo/. Enables the app to appear with a
    proper description in GNOME Software, KDE Discover, and other
    AppStream-indexing software stores.
  * Packaging: build-appimage.sh now implements the full python-appimage ->
    extract AppDir -> linuxdeploy-plugin-gtk -> AppImage pipeline. Gated
    behind repo variable APPIMAGE_READY=1 until end-to-end tested.

